tates. Of interest to historians of labor, law, maritime culture, and national identity in the early republic, Raffety’s work reveals much about the ways that merchant seamen sought to articulate the ideals of freedom and citizenship before the courts of the land—and how they helped to shape the laws of the young republic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMaritime law -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 0aMaritime lawzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMerchant mariners -- Legal status, laws, etc. -- United States -- History -- 19th century. 0aMerchant marinersxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUnited States -- History -- 1815-1861. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022692400740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226924014423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226924014/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles